00:59:29.640 --> 00:59:30.940
&gt;&gt; Patricia Kennedy Grimsted: Well,

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:34.980
thank you for raising
that question, Jim.

00:59:34.980 --> 00:59:36.610
This is very important.

00:59:36.610 --> 00:59:45.780
A Belaruse colleague whom I first
met in 2003, when I was in Minsk.

00:59:45.780 --> 00:59:49.720
He's now, I think, close to 90.

00:59:49.720 --> 00:59:56.060
He had been the Belaruse
SSR, the Soviet Republic

00:59:56.060 --> 01:00:00.910
of Belaruse UNESCO
Representative in Paris in,

01:00:00.910 --> 01:00:04.040
I think he said the
late '50s or '60s.

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:10.230
And he just said -- told me, he
said, you know, it was very sad

01:00:10.230 --> 01:00:17.820
for me when I met the widow of
Leon Bloom or the Luis Vise,

01:00:17.820 --> 01:00:21.780
who was a leading feminist,
journalist, in France,

01:00:21.780 --> 01:00:25.310
that I couldn't return
or even tell them

01:00:25.310 --> 01:00:27.760
that they're books were in Minsk.

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:30.770 position:56%
He has written some lovely articles,

01:00:30.770 --> 01:00:33.310
most of them are in
Russian or Belaruse.

01:00:33.310 --> 01:00:40.020
There are a couple in English that
I cite in my article about some

01:00:40.020 --> 01:00:42.040
of the relations to the --

01:00:42.040 --> 01:00:48.470
the archival, personal archival
information that's in those books.

01:00:48.470 --> 01:00:53.130
Because these are books with
very famous French autographs

01:00:53.130 --> 01:00:56.930
of leading statesmen
and [inaudible].

01:00:56.930 --> 01:01:02.630
And he's done a beautiful job
of showing the dedications,

01:01:02.630 --> 01:01:11.260 position:56%
in some cases to people who perished
in [foreign word] or Auschwitz.

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:13.400
He's done the research on it.

01:01:13.400 --> 01:01:18.560
He was a rector of the School
of Linguistics in Prague,

01:01:18.560 --> 01:01:22.240
a specialist from French
language and literature.

01:01:22.240 --> 01:01:25.310
And he's particularly
researched these books.

01:01:25.310 --> 01:01:32.510
And last summer in Paris I met
one and I think that this --

01:01:32.510 --> 01:01:35.470
the young historian,
the Belaruse historian,

01:01:35.470 --> 01:01:38.850
who now is helping arrange
our seminar in Minsk,

01:01:38.850 --> 01:01:42.300
was a student of his because
he spoke very good French.

01:01:42.300 --> 01:01:46.560
And I think it was his
first trip outside Belaruse.

01:01:46.560 --> 01:01:52.690
But he was on a stipend that a
Paris friend of mine had arranged,

01:01:52.690 --> 01:01:56.870
and he gave a lecture at
the Institute of France

01:01:56.870 --> 01:02:04.010
about the anti-Dreyfus documents
and manuscripts of several

01:02:04.010 --> 01:02:10.500 position:56%
of the leaders, Jewish leaders, that
were -- about the Dreyfus affair,

01:02:10.500 --> 01:02:14.990 position:56%
because these were books the Nazis
obviously had been trying to capture

01:02:14.990 --> 01:02:18.110
from Joseph Reinach and
his family in Paris.

01:02:18.110 --> 01:02:22.490
And so this is the kind of
information that is there.

01:02:22.490 --> 01:02:27.290
And these were manuscripts from
Joseph Reinach that were --

01:02:27.290 --> 01:02:29.750
had never been catalogued
before in --

01:02:29.750 --> 01:02:33.480
but Minsk and because
no one wanted them

01:02:33.480 --> 01:02:36.080
or they were all suppressed
during the Soviet period.

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:39.670
And he's writing a
doctoral dissertation

01:02:39.670 --> 01:02:43.300
about the Masonic manuscripts
that are there.

01:02:43.300 --> 01:02:47.000
And it turns out that
they are fragments

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:56.320
of the same Masonic archives that
were returned from Moscow to Paris

01:02:56.320 --> 01:03:03.640
by the year 2000 because archives
that were found in Minsk all had

01:03:03.640 --> 01:03:08.400
to be sent to Moscow after the
war, but not all the books.

01:03:08.400 --> 01:03:14.110
And so they were all collected
in this central repository

01:03:14.110 --> 01:03:17.620
for the special archive
that I described

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:20.800
in this book, <i>Return from Russia </i>.

01:03:20.800 --> 01:03:23.560
And so these are the
types of materials that --

01:03:23.560 --> 01:03:29.960
he's written some lovely -- I just
heard that he is still able to come

01:03:29.960 --> 01:03:36.300
and that he's agreed to come to our
seminar next September in Minsk.

01:03:36.300 --> 01:03:41.390
We're just keeping it very small,
a mission, that we're trying to --

01:03:41.390 --> 01:03:44.050
and I hope to meet him again.

01:03:44.050 --> 01:03:47.550
But he has a card file
if sine if the books

01:03:47.550 --> 01:03:53.020
that he found particularly
important for the dedications,

01:03:53.020 --> 01:03:57.590
for the interpersonal relations
that they show in these dedications

01:03:57.590 --> 01:04:00.220
in the books, let alone
the books themselves.

01:04:00.220 --> 01:04:04.320
I mean, some of these are
from bibliophile collections

01:04:04.320 --> 01:04:07.330
of the Rothschild's
from the 18th century.

01:04:07.330 --> 01:04:12.160
I mean they're -- the rare book
department that I had the catalog,

01:04:12.160 --> 01:04:15.730
the only books from rare books,

01:04:15.730 --> 01:04:20.080
and what are these
books needed in Minsk.

01:04:20.080 --> 01:04:21.380
There's no one.

01:04:21.380 --> 01:04:22.790
I think this young man that we met

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:26.690
in Paris last summer is
probably the first to --

01:04:26.690 --> 01:04:30.780
